One solution is to `fetch` the page and use a regular expression to extract the content of the meta description. It seems a bit weird to do that to be honest and you might run into CORS issues.

A better solution would be to send a request to your server to extract the meta header from the page.

```js
fetch(&#39;https://example.com/items/123456&#39;)
  .then(res =&gt; res.text())
  .then(text =&gt; text.match(/&lt;meta description=&quot;([^&quot;]+)&quot;&gt;/i))
  .then(meta =&gt; {
    // meta is null if there&#39;s no match and otherwise meta[1] will contain the item description.
    if(meta) {
      $(&#39;#thedescription&#39;).html(meta[1]);
    }
  })
```

